Comment: The king's pawn opening. My usual opening move as white. Gives my queen and light-square bishop freedom, and potentially threatens checkmate quickly.
The king's pawn game. My opponent is possibly hoping to checkmate quickly, too.
The centre game. I have a high success rate with this opening sequence of moves. My dark-square bishop is free, too, and I have control of three diagonals.
He develops his knight to attack my queen's pawn and defend his king's pawn...
...so we swap pawns...
...so we swap pawns...
...and I delay bringing out my queen one move, instead attacking his knight with mine...
...and we swap knights. My queen sits nicely on the 3rd rank, placing me ahead on development.
...and we swap knights. My queen sits nicely on the 3rd rank, placing me ahead on development.
He now develops his remaining knight...
...so I develop my dark-square bishop, attacking the knight, forcing it to act as a pin for the queen...
...and I develop my remaining knight, allowing me to castle queenside...
...and I develop my remaining knight, allowing me to castle queenside...
...and he moves out his bishop to allow his knight to move away, and to castle kingside...
...and I castle queenside, placing my rook on the d-file, threatening e5, a pawn fork on the d6-pawn and knight...
...and he castles kingside to allow this to happen...
...here. If he keeps his knight on f6, he either loses it for a pawn, or he loses his queen for a rook and pawn...
...so he moves it out of harm's way...
...so we trade bishops...
...so we trade bishops...
...and pawns, creating an isolated pawn on d6...
...and pawns, creating an isolated pawn on d6...
...so I line it up with my queen, covered by her rook...
...and remove it, giving me the slightest of advantages - a single pawn.
...and remove it, giving me the slightest of advantages - a single pawn.
Now he checks my king with his queen...
